Equation~\ref{eq:IPARX} (repeated below for convenience)
is our conceptual framework for considering sustainability.
Chapter~\ref{chap:planetary_boundaries} discussed planetary boundaries and the impact
of human activities on those boundaries, that is, the left-hand side of Equation~\ref{eq:IPARX}.
Chapter~\ref{chap:population} is about the first term on the right-hand side of 
Equation~\ref{eq:IPARX}, world population and its dynamics. 
Discussion questions from Chapter~\ref{chap:population} reveal a variety of ways 
in which it is practically and morally difficult to reduce impacts~($I$) by reducing 
population~($P$).
This chapter examines the second term on the right-hand side of Equation~\ref{eq:IPARX},
affluence~($A$), and the role of human economic activity in sustainability challenges.
Chapters~\ref{chap:resource_intensity}--\ref{chap:impact_intensity}, 
finish the development of our framework for sustainability.

\begin{equation} 
  \iparx            \tag{\ref{eq:IPARX}}
\end{equation}


%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
\section{Global affluence}
\label{sec:Global_affluence}
%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%

The word wealth can include notions of happiness, prosperity, well being, and welfare,
but mostly wealth refers to the \emph{amount} of goods, possessions, money,
property, or ``stuff'' owned by a person.
In other words, wealth refers to a \emph{level} of material possessions or resources.
In contrast, affluence ($A$) is the \emph{rate} that the economy
uses goods and services, that is, the amount of ``stuff'' bought \emph{per year}.

Economic activity may mean literally consumption, as in the case with food,
or it could mean using a service, such as education or getting a haircut.
Sometimes, what is ``consumed'' is ancillary to what the consumer actually desires.
For example, when a person travels from point A to point B,
whether the car is electric or burns gasoline doesnâ€™t matter (to the traveler).
The energy consumed is just a means to an end, often called the ``service.''
(In this example, the energy service is travel.)

Average affluence \Aparen{} for a country or the world
is \emph{measured} by gross domestic product (GDP) per capita.
There are valid critiques as to why per capita GDP is not the \emph{best possible}
measure of affluence.
For instance, GDP doesn't count (or under counts) the value
of innovation in improving standards of living~\cite{Gordon2016}.
Many new metrics (Section~\ref{sec:indices}) have been proposed as replacements
or improvements for GDP.
Some examples are green GDP, the index of sustainable economic welfare, and the
genuine progress indicator.
However, each of these suffers from its own limitations. %, philosophical, methodological, and practical.
The biggest limitation is standardization and availability of data.
GDP is what we have the most data for and, consequently,
it is the affluence indicator ``everyone'' uses.
Effectively, GDP is the standard way to measure economic activity.
(Because GDP data are collected nationally but aggregated internationally, 
there is often skepticism of data provided by corrupt and/or authoritarian
regimes, in addition to the caveats about what GDP measures and what it doesn't.)
% put in the streetlight effect, McNamara's fallacy, and/or Goodhart's law?

Consistent and easily accessible GDP data allows us to make observations
about trends, which are \emph{qualitatively} consistent with trends we would observe
using other indices, bearing in mind the limitations of what GDP measures and what it doesn't.
In any case, a different measure of affluence~($A$), would require a corresponding
adjustment to (the measure of) resource intensity of economic activity~($R$).
Regardless of the measure of affluence, we land in the same difficult spot:
greater affluence~($A$) creates greater environmental impact~($I$)
if the resource intensity of the economy~($R$) and the impact intensity of resources~($X$)
(discussed in the next chapter) are unchanged.

Figures~\ref{fig:AffluenceGraph-Nordhaus} and~\ref{fig:GDPGraph-Nordhaus} show
world annual GDP per capita and total GDP, respectively.
Note that many national and international economic policies are intended to
continually increase affluence and/or maintain growth in GDP.
Figures~\ref{fig:AffluenceGraph-Nordhaus} and~\ref{fig:GDPGraph-Nordhaus} show
that these choices have been effective.
(Recall that Section~\ref{sec:exp} reminds us that perpetual growth in the 
consumption of finite resources is ultimately unsustainable.)

