GDP is denominated in units of money and is the sum of four terms:

\begin{equation}
\label{eq:GDP}
  GDP = c + g + i + nx \; .
\end{equation}

%..............................
\paragraph{Consumption}
%..............................

Consumption~($c$) is purchases made by individuals.
Typically, consumption is about two thirds of GDP for developed economies and is
usually divided into three subcategories: durable goods, nondurable goods, and services.
Services represent nontangible things, such as haircuts, legal advice, education,
and concert tickets.
Durable goods are defined as things that last longer than 3 years,
such as appliances and automobiles.
Nondurable goods are things that are consumed immediately, like food, paper, or fuel.
Fabrics, like clothes or carpet, are counted as nondurable goods, even if they
happen to last more than three years.
Durable goods spending is more sensitive to economic conditions than nondurable
goods spending,
because consumers can usually choose to postpone spending on durable goods
until circumstances improve.


%..............................
\paragraph{Government spending}
%..............................

Government spending~($g$) is comprised of government consumption
(such as equipment and wages paid to government workers) and net investment, for
example, infrastructure improvements.


%..............................
\paragraph{Investment}
%..............................

Investment~($i$) is \emph{not} money put into a bank account.
Investment is goods that are purchased now for use in the future.
There are three subcategories of investment: nonresidential fixed investment,
residential fixed investment, and inventory investment.
Nonresidential fixed investment is equipment and plants (factories) purchased by firms.
In contrast, residential fixed investment is the purchase of housing stock by
households and landlords.
Inventory investment is the purchase, by firms, of goods for later sale and could
be negative (inventory is falling) or positive (inventory is increasing).


%..............................
\paragraph{Net exports}
%..............................

Net exports~($nx$) are the \emph{net} difference between the value of exports and the value of imports.
Thus, $nx$ could be a negative number for a country that imports more than it exports.
World GDP is the sum of all national GDPs.
Therefore, for world GDP, $nx = 0$.
We don't import from or export to space, \ldots yet.


%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
\subsection{Production/Affluence balance}
\label{sec:PCbalance}
%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++

Although economists use consumption narrowly as described in Equation~\ref{eq:GDP},
we use the term colloquially to mean the sum of personal consumption, 
government spending, and investment.
That is, we use the term ``consumption'' to mean global GDP, in part to remind ourselves
that economic activity is based on the use of resources.
Individuals and corporations may ``save'' money for purchases in the future, but the
economy as a whole balances production and (this more generic form of) consumption as 
closely as possible, such that

\begin{equation} \label{eq:PCbalance}
  \mathrm{Production} = \mathrm{Consumption} \; .
\end{equation}
%
Money that is invested in a bank is lent out to borrowers so that they can make
purchases.
Money invested in the stock market is used by companies to purchase equipment, 
do research, or grow the business in some other way.
Goods and services must be produced before they can be used.
There is no incentive to produce goods that aren't used;
why would you pay the costs of production if there were no prospects of a sale?
% Storage and maintenance costs further discourage excess production.
% Note that temporary ``buffering'' is categorically different from a long-term 
% imbalance of excess production. 
% Many agricultural products are harvested in a short period of time and then stored 
% and sold at uniform rate.
% Selling apples throughout the year out of cold storage facilities is not the same
% as growing apples that no one will ever eat.
% Likewise, inventory investment (mentioned above) is a relatively short-term expense
% to have goods available when customers want them, not a long-term difference in
% supply and demand.
%
Therefore, we use the terms ``production'' and ``consumption'' interchangeably.


%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
\subsection{Economic metabolism}
\label{sec:econ_metab}
%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++

Having established that the economy only consumes what the economy produces and,
likewise, only things that will be consumed are produced, we are ready to introduce
the metaphor of the economic metabolism.
All plant and animal metabolisms consume resources
(energy and materials) 
and produce wastes in the process of doing useful things.
Similarly, economies take in resources and produce wastes.

%^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^
\begin{mcframe}[0.90\textwidth](0.85\textwidth)
%^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^

Thus, the economy is society's metabolism.

\end{mcframe}

One way of looking at Equation~\ref{eq:IPARX} is that impacts ($I$)
are the \emph{result} of economic activity.
That is, environmental impacts are the result of society's metabolism.
Total consumption (that is, world GDP) is $P \times A$ in Equation~\ref{eq:IPARX}.
Resources ($R$) are the feed the economy needs to live and grow.
The impact intensity of resources~($X$) 
represents the wastes that the economy excretes.


%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
\section{Economic growth and contraction}
\label{sec:EconGrowth}
%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%

Although production and consumption are in balance, both may change together.
Indeed, growth in GDP per capita~($A$) is the explicit goal of many economic policies.
There are two ways the economy can increase GDP.
Either (a)~the economy consumes \emph{more} inputs or
(b)~it uses existing inputs more \emph{efficiently}.

Economic inputs include labor, capital, energy, and materials.
In the long run, growing output by scaling up the inputs does not increase 
affluence~($A$) because more workers are needed to gather, process, and use the 
additional resources.
That leaves only efficiency as a means of boosting affluence.
From a sustainability point of view, we should want to everything to be used
as efficiently as possible; inefficiency of any kind is not desirable.

The productivity of labor depends on the education and skill 
of workers, technology, the number of workers in the population, the number of hours they 
work, and the fraction of the population that is working;
see Section~\ref{sec:dtt}.
More workers will increase economic output but will not increase GDP \emph{per person}.
A greater fraction of the population working, such as with the demographic dividend, 
or workers working longer hours will tend to increase $A$ (at least until the 
population pyramid stabilizes, in the case of the demographic dividend).

Capital is buildings, equipment, machines, and tools---\emph{things}
that make workers more productive.
For instance, a builder with a backhoe can excavate a foundation faster than a
builder with only a shovel.
More capital investment \emph{sometimes} means greater economic output.
Because capital depreciates over time, continual investment 
(part of $i$ in Equation~\ref{eq:GDP})
is needed to maintain a certain level of capital stock. 
Higher levels of capital require larger yearly investments to maintain.
At some point, there is a \emph{maximum} level of effective capital.
Beyond that maximum, additional capital is more expensive to maintain than it contributes 
to the economy.
% The maximum effective level depends on technology and the price of borrowing
% money (that is, interest) for making capital investments.
% Conceptually, 
At the effective maximum level of effective capital, labor will have a maximum
level of output because workers are fully ``tooled up.''

Innovation is the major source of economic growth.
There are two types of innovation: the invention of new \emph{kinds} of goods and
services \emph{or} improvements to efficiency.
The majority of the goods and services we consume today did not exist in 
1870~\cite{Gordon2016}.
Today, we consume entirely new categories of goods and services that did not
exist for most of human history.
Much of the improvement in our standard of living comes from these innovations.

However, examined closely, almost all of these ``new goods'' stories 
\emph{also} end up being about some form of efficiency.
The endless quest to meet our needs more efficiently allows us to instead spend
our budget on \emph{additional} consumption.
Efficiency improvements allow us to get more GDP for the same level of resource consumption.
However, as we will see in Chapter~\ref{chap:resource_intensity}, particularly in 
Figures~\ref{fig:per_capita_material_use} and~\ref{fig:EnergyPerPersonGraph},
economic growth results in \emph{more} consumption of resources.
The greater use of resources is caused by affluence growth, 
driven, in part, by improvements in material (Figure~\ref{fig:per_gdp_material_use})
and energy (Figure~\ref{fig:EnergyIntensityGraph-Nordhaus}) efficiency 
(that is, ``innovation,'' as defined above).
