Economies can grow (particularly when we try to make them grow) but they can also
shrink.
A shrinking economy is said to be in recession.
A full discussion of the mechanisms of recession is beyond the scope of this book
but the effect of recessions can be seen in Figure~\ref{fig:CarbonEmissionsGraph}.
If affluence $A$ is a cause of impacts $I$, then reducing $A$ is one way to reduce
$I$, as Figure~\ref{fig:CarbonEmissionsGraph} shows for CO$_2$ emissions.
However, recessions are unwelcome for many very good reasons. 
No country has yet intentionally tried to shrink its economy.

Moreover, the environmental effects of recessions are not always positive,
that is, sometimes reducing $A$ \emph{increases} (at least some parts of) $I$.
For instance, a company going out of business might cause 
environmental contamination because there no longer exists a responsible steward for 
potentially hazardous materials or equipment.
The U.S.\ has hundreds of thousands of leaking underground gasoline storage tanks
from gas stations that have gone out of business~\cite{brownfields}.
Similar stories can be told for former industrial sites, mines, and oil and gas wells.

What if there were ways to reduce the size of the economy that did not
generate the negative effects of a recession?
The next section examines some ideas that have been proposed as alternatives
to continued economic growth.
(Note that we \emph{examine} these ideas without necessarily \emph{endorsing} them.)

%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
\section{Zero growth, degrowth, and alternative economic models}
\label{sec:circular_economy}
%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%

World economies are managed for continued growth. 
% (See P1.\ref{project:alt_exp} for the relationship between continual growth
% and exponential growth.)
As mentioned previously, continual growth is inherently
unsustainable on a finite planet.
When the economy grows continually it will, at some point,
either demand more resources than the environment can provide or
exceed the ecosystem's ability to absorb wastes.
Eventually, economic growth will push the ecosystem past a tipping point where the
ecosystem is no longer able to provide ecosystem services, as 
discussed in Chapter~\ref{chap:planetary_boundaries}.

In response, there are calls for transitioning world economies 
to new operating regimes, different from growth. 
There are proposals for 
zero-growth (or steady-state), 
degrowth (or shrinking),  
circular, and 
doughnut
economies. 


%..............................
\paragraph{Steady state} 
%..............................

A steady-state economy\index{economy!steady-state} is one that neither grows nor shrinks.
Its size (measured in \$/year) stays the same through time.
A steady-state economy would experience no change in the standard of living from 
one generation to the next,
as was (nearly) the case in the ancient and medieval worlds.

A steady-state economy is not inherently sustainable.
In fact, the sustainability of an economy is not determined by its growth rate
(usually measured in \%/year). 
Rather, the sustainability of an economy is determined by its \emph{level} or \emph{size}
(usually measured in \$/year). 
If the steady-state level of the economy 
is above a sustainable threshold
(if planetary limits have been exceeded), 
the economy is unsustainable, regardless of whether it is growing (positive \%/year), 
shrinking (negative \%/year)  or 
steady state (0 \%/year). 
Indeed, Figure~\ref{fig:FootprintHDIGraph} suggests that
many economies are \emph{already} too large to be considered sustainable.

Figure~\ref{fig:FootprintHDIGraph} further highlights the fact that 
many economies are \emph{both} already too large and still growing.
For those economies, a transition to steady state can be a first step 
toward becoming sustainable. 
A transition to steady state means that 
those economies will not grow to be \emph{more} unsustainable each year. 

%..............................
\paragraph{Degrowth} \index{degrowth}
%..............................

In contrast to the steady-state economy, 
degrowth advocates embrace the fact that many economies need to become smaller
to be sustainable.
There are substantial social and political pressures against degrowth.
And for good reason!
Degrowth implies a reduction in the standard of living.
Although Figure~\ref{fig:FootprintHDIGraph} implies a lower standard of living
is necessary for sustainability, accepting a drastically lower standard of 
living is extremely unpalatable for most people.
Furthermore, there are costs and difficulties associated with \emph{transitioning}\index{transition!economic}
from one type of economy to another. 
The costs are real and, to date,
there has been no political will or action to make 
such a transition in the amount of time it would take to avoid a climate
crisis.

%..............................
\paragraph{Circular economy} \index{economy!circular}
%..............................

Another alternative to today's growth economies
is a \emph{circular} economy\index{economy!circular}, 
which (a)~consumes only recycled (and, perhaps, renewable) materials and energy
and (b)~emits no waste. 
A circular economy is impossible to achieve completely.
Materials cannot be 100\% recycled and, for many materials, the recycling process
degrades material properties. 
The biggest flaw in a circular economy is that it requires continual energy input,
in part because recycling of materials requires energy
(see Section~\ref{sec:recycling}).
Lastly, it is not clear that a circular economy can be \emph{economically} sustainable.

That said, the circular economy provides a helpful model to strive toward.
Achieving circular economies will bring us much closer to sustainability.

%..............................
\paragraph{Doughnut economy} \index{economy!doughnut}
%..............................

A doughnut economy is a name for attempting to keep the size of economic activity
within planetary boundaries (represented by an outer circle) while simultaneously
attempting to lift people out of poverty (represented by an inner circle).
The space between the two circles is the doughnut and is the ``safe operating 
space'' for humanity. 
The outer circle is a form of steady-state economy (perhaps changing as technology
changes).
However, one criticism of a steady-state economy is that (some) people could be left
poor and destitute. 
The doughnut economy thus attempts to impose both a ``floor'' and a ``ceiling'' 
on economic activity and tries to respect planetary boundaries by equalizing income 
disparity between rich and poor.

While a doughnut economy might sound good in theory, there would be many conceptual and
operational difficulties in implementation. 
To one degree or another these are difficulties shared with the steady-state,
degrowth, and circular economy models.
First, tying economic level(s) to particular planetary boundaries might not be
straightforward, particularly since we don't know with certainty exactly what those 
boundaries are in some cases.
Probably, a better approach is to address, for example, CO$_2$ emissions directly.
Second, there are no successful templates for degrowth to the outside of the doughnut
(if necessary) and then managing distribution of affluence within the doughnut.
Relatedly, who sets the ``floor'' and the time period for transition?
Third, the doughnut model implicitly sets up a ``people-versus-planet'' dichotomy
and then attempts to maximize the ``people'' part of the equation 
(to the extent permitted by the ``planet'' part of the equation).
Might it be possible to have flourishing for people \emph{and} planet?

%^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^
\begin{mcframe}[0.90\textwidth](0.85\textwidth)
%^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^

These alternative economic models raise the question:
what do we really want from life?
Is it really economic growth that we desire?
Or do we desire 
(1)~enough food shelter to survive?
(2)~Safety?
(3)~Love and belonging?
(4)~The esteem of family, friends, and others?
(5)~Some form of self-actualization?
The above hierarchy of needs~\cite{Maslow1954}, 
can frame the question of ``what do we really want?''

The recent work of Lina Brand-Correa, Julia Steinberger, and others
frame the question of ``what do we want from life'' in energy terms~\cite{Brand-Correa:2017aa}.
They search for ways to decouple satisfaction of human needs from 
energy services, energy consumption, and CO$_2$ emissions.

\end{mcframe}

Despite the limitations mentioned above, alternative economic models suggest 
helpful ways of thinking about affluence from a sustainability perspective.

