Many proposals for becoming more sustainable are effectively reductions of
affluence. 
Poverty is a hard sell on an individual level; no one wants it for themselves.
(An abstract desire to have lower impacts is not the same as wanting to be poor.)
Lower levels of affluence are associated with lower HDI, as 
Figure~\ref{fig:FootprintHDIGraph} shows (because income is a factor in HDI).

Some people \emph{have} chosen (relative) poverty by trying to escape the economic
system; see P4.\ref{project:off-grid} for a few examples.
Often, for these people, independence or being ``off grid'' is the main attraction.
However, even for these people, there is no escaping a relationship to the rest of
humanity.
There is always some participation in the broader economy,
so there is no escaping the sustainability implications of economic activity.

